  "prompt": "What is the difference between shear stress and shear strain?",
  "response": "Shear stress and shear strain are both measures related to the deformation of a material, but they represent different aspects of that deformation.\n\nShear stress is the measure of the force applied parallel or tangential to a surface, per unit area. It is a measure of the internal resistance of a material to the deforming forces. It is typically measured in units of force per unit area, such as Pascals (Pa) or pounds per square inch (psi).\n\nShear strain, on the other hand, is a measure of the deformation or displacement that results from the application of a shear stress. It is defined as the ratio of the displacement or deformation of the material to its original dimensions. It is a dimensionless quantity, often expressed as a percentage or in radians.\n\nIn summary, shear stress is the force causing the deformation, while shear strain is the resulting deformation itself. The relationship between the two is described by the material's shear modulus, which is a measure of the material's stiffness or resistance to shear deformation.",
